      • mergeTCPInfo

        public NavPoint mergeTCPInfo(NavPoint point)
        Creates a new point that is the merger of the this point and the given point. Assumes that mergeable() on the two points would return true, if not, then approximately the original point is returned.

        Merging rules:

        • mergeTCPInfo() is commutative
        • If both points are linear points, then the points are merged.
        • If one point is a linear point (aka, not a TCP), then the TCP info (velocity and acceleration) from the TCP point is used.
        • If both points are TCP (aka acceleration points) of different types (Trk, Gs, Vs), then the points should merge without an issue, note: they are required to have the same "velocity in"
        • If both points are TCP (aka acceleration points) of the same type (Trk, Gs, or Vs), then the resulting point should be a combined point (e.g., EOTBOT), and the TCP information should be the information from the beginning point.
        • If both points are TCP "begin" points, then a message is provided if they have different source positions
        Parameters:
        point - the other point
        Returns:
        a new point that is the merger of the two points.

      • velocityIn

        public Velocity velocityIn()
        If this is a TCP, return the velocity in metadata. Otherwise return an invalid velocity. Not that this value is only well-defined for two case: the beginning of acceleration points (BGSC, BVSC, BOT) and points with a fixed gs mutability (where trk and vs may still not be well-defined)

      • trkAccel

        public double trkAccel()
        Return the (signed) turn rate (i.e., position acceleration in the "track" dimension) associated with this point. Turn rate is in rad/sec (positive is clockwise/right, negative is counterclockwise/left), otherwise return 0.0;

      • linearEst

        public NavPoint linearEst(Velocity vo,
                          double tm)
        Compute a new lat/lon that is obtained by moving with velocity vo for tm secs This is a computationally fast estimate, and only should be used for relatively short distances. Negative time is a projection in the opposite direction (along the same great circle, if in latlon) and into the past
        Parameters:
        vo - velocity away from original position
        tm - time of relocation
        Returns:
        new lat/lon position in direction v0

      • parseMetaDataLabel

        public NavPoint parseMetaDataLabel()
        If it is detected that this string uses the old metatdata format, this returns an invalid NavPoint.

      • parseMetaDataLabel

        public NavPoint parseMetaDataLabel(java.lang.String tlabel)
        This parses the label generated for TCP types to reconstruct the meta-data of the point. It returns either the same point (if no significant data is in the label) or a fully reconstructed TCP type. The reconstructed TCP will have a label field that does not contain any TCP metadata -- you will need to call name() or tcpLabel() to retrieve the full string. If it is detected that this string uses the old metatdata format, this returns an invalid NavPoint.
